ige</i> ‘victory’ + <i>weald</i> ‘rule(r)’, or the corresponding Old Norse <i>Sigvaldr</i>. This name later became thoroughly confused with <i>Sewal(d)</i>, from Old English <i>Sǣweald</i> (see   Sewall  ).","habitational name from one or more places, such as Sewell (Bedfordshire), Seawell (Northamptonshire), Sywell (Northamptonshire), Showell in Steeple Barton (Oxfordshire), Showell in Little Tew (Oxfordshire), or Sowell in Kentisbeare (Devon), all meaning ‘seven springs’ (Old English <i>seofon</i> + <i>wella</i>). Compare   Seawell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Seawell","meanings":["English: variant of   Sewell   and   Sewall  ."]},{"name":"Sewall","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Sewal(d)</i>, <i>Sawal(d)</i>, Old English <i>Sǣweald</i>, from <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>weald</i> ‘rule(r)’. This name later became thoroughly confused with <i>Sewal(d)</i> from Old English <i>Sigeweald</i> or Old Norse <i>Sigvaldr</i> (see   Sewell  ). Compare   Seawell  .","variant of   Sewell  ."]},{"name":"Showell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]},{"name":"Shewell","meanings":["English: variant of   Sewell   with palatalization of the initial <i>S-</i>. The pronunciation may have been influenced through folk etymology by the English dialect word <i>shewel</i>, for a scarecrow."]},{"name":"Suell","meanings":["Generally, this is a shortened form of   Michelle  , respelled by association with the vocabulary word. In some cases it may be a shortened form of   Shelley ."]},{"name":"Sowell","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname of a well-known New England family, whose members included the poet  Robert Lowell  (  1917–77 ). The surname is a variant of   Lovell ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":46,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Sewell Eatington was born in 1060, in Ettington, Warwickshire, England. She married Sewell de Eatington before 1085. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1060–":"1060–Surnud","1058–1129":"1058–1129","1085–1148":"1085–1148","1096–1141":"1096–1141","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","about 1085":"umbes 1085","about 1096":"umbes 1096","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1148":"1148",